elf, become visible once the city can leverage their creativity to benefit economic revitalization and gentrification. He points to the creative cultural practices that young people of color from low-income communities use to resist their subjectification as members of an underclass, which, along with redistributive economic policies, can be deployed as an effective means with which to both oppose gentrification and better serve the youth who have become emblematic of urban creativity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aAfrican American youthxEducation (Secondary)zRhode IslandzProvidence. 0aArts and youthzRhode IslandzProvidence. 0aArtszRhode IslandzProvidence. 0aGentrificationzRhode IslandzProvidence. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2019z978311069632540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478007319zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478007319423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478007319.jpg  a978-3-11-069632-5  DUK eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles